A bruteforce solution I did to train a little bit on my programming.


M_ind converts between single matrix index and x,y indices

# convert single index v_i to i,j 
M_ind <- function(v_i) {
  i = 9 # dim of sudoku
  i_m = ifelse(v_i%%i,v_i%%i,i)
  return(c(i_m,ceiling(v_i/i)))
}

I found this solution a while ago by answering a stackoverflow question.
Getting the 3x3 “boxes” of the sudoku:

# create boxes
boxes <- matrix(
  sapply(list(1:3,4:6,7:9),rep,3,each=3),
  9,byrow = TRUE
)

there might be a more elegant way, but this will do it for now…



Checking if the number at x,y is unique in its row, column and box.

is_valid <- function(X,Y,board,boxes) {
  box   <- boxes[X,Y] 
  if (any(duplicated(board[X,],incomparables = 0))) {
    return(FALSE)
  } else if (any(duplicated(board[,Y],incomparables = 0))) {
    return(FALSE)
  } else if (any(duplicated(board[boxes==box],incomparables = 0))){
    return(FALSE)
  } else {
    return(TRUE)
  } 
}


using apply here would have made the whole thing even slower :(

Now the main function:

# depth first search
solve_sudoku <- function(sudoku) {
  solved = FALSE
  empty = which(sudoku == 0)
  N = 1
  while (solved == FALSE) {
    if(N == length(empty)+1){
      solved = TRUE
      break
    }
    i <- M_ind(empty[N]) 
    while(sudoku[empty[N]] <= 9){
      sudoku[empty[N]] = sudoku[empty[N]] + 1
      check = is_valid(X=i[1],Y=i[2],board=sudoku,boxes = boxes)
      if(sudoku[empty[N]] > 9){
        sudoku[empty[N]] <- 0
        N = N - 1
        break
      }
      if(check) {
        N = N + 1
        break
      }
   }
  }
  return(sudoku)
}

